AGI - SpaceX successfully launched the "Fram2>" mission to fly over the North and South Earth poles, with a crew of four non-professional astronauts on board. This is a new step in the commercial exploration of space and a new ambitious goal cut by the company of Elon Musk.>&nbsp;
Scream of joy and relief accompanied the take-off of the 4 private adventurers aboard a Dragon> capsule, transported by a Falcon 9,> rocket as shown by images broadcast live on the official website of SpaceX. To take part in this private mission, named Fram2 in homage to a ship used for polar exploration in the nineteenth century, are people with different profiles, all not astronauts by profession.
<div </div
"With the same pioneering spirit as the first polar explorers, we try to bring new knowledge and data back to advance space exploration in the long term," said the mission commander, Chun Wang>, entrepreneurs enriched in the cryptocurrency sector and shipowner. The Norwegian director Jannicke Mikkelsen >, the Australian Eric Philips >, expert guide of polar explorations, and the German researcher in robotics Rabea Rogge >.
<div </div
The mission should last between three and five days and involves the realization of over 20 scientific experiments, including the first radiographic images in space and the cultivation of mushrooms in microgravity. The crew trained for eight months, even in difficult conditions, in Alaska. Upon returning to Earth, the 4 will try to get out of the capsule without medical assistance, as part of a study aimed at understanding what tasks can be performed independently by astronauts after a space flight.
CNN, in his 'live' dedicated to the mission, reported the first words of a Space X controller to the crew: "We are honored to transport you safely to your polar orbit. Enjoy the view, send us some photos and our hearts will be with you as you fly over the poles, good flight." &nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
